File Cabinet (Furniture type). Furniture with sliding drawers for storing files.
Shelf (Furniture type). Furniture for storing books or other items.
Sofa (Furniture type). Furniture for seating multiple people.
Table (Furniture type). Furniture with a countertop for multiple people.
Technical Cabinet (Furniture type). A technical cabinet is a piece of furniture for holding, displaying and protecting technical appliances, usually organized in shelves, drawers or racks.

Geometric Model. Representation of the concept of a volumetric geological and geotechnical model, usually an interpretation but sometimes created direct from ground penetrating measurement.
The assembly may contain one of more strata and other anthropic elements. The contained subtypes of IfcGeotechnicalStratum will have shape representations made from polyhedra or surfaces if a 'Yabuki' top surface model is being used.

Geoslice. Representation of the concept of a sectional planar geological and geotechnical model, usually an interpretation but sometimes created direct from ground penetrating measurement. The assembly may contain one of more strata and anthropic elements. The contained subtypes of IfcGeotechnicalStratum will have shape representations made from polygons reflecting the visible section or poly lines if a 'Yabuki' top surface model is being used.

Geotechnical Assembly. Representation of the abstract concept of a geological and geotechnical model, usually an interpretation but sometimes created direct from ground penetrating measurement.
Use of an assembly is optional but can carry the methodology and uncertainty information.
Such assemblies will include IfcGeotechnicalStratum entity types and may include other entity types such as IfcPile, IfcSlab or IfcSensor to represent the capping, lining or logging equipment present.
IfcBorehole or IfcGeoSlice  can have a physical reality as a construction hazard alongside being the carrier for the interpreted results. Geological hazards may be associated to any IfcGeotechnicalAssembly or IfcGeotechnicalStratum.

Geotechnical Stratum. Representation of the concept of an identified discrete almost homogeneous geological feature with either an irregular solid or 'Yabuki' top surface shape or a regular voxel cubic shape. A stratum is represented as a discrete entity, specialised (sub typed) from IfcElement. A stratum may be broken down into smaller entities if properties vary across the stratum or alternatively properties may be described with bounded numeric ranges. A stratum may carry information about the physical form and its interpretation as a Geological Item (GML).
The shape representations used should correspond to the sub-type of IfcGeotechnicalAssembly in which it occurs

Solid (Geotechnical Stratum type). Representation of the concept of an identified discrete almost homogenous solid geological or surface feature, including discontinuities such as faults, fractures, boundaries and interfaces that are not explicitly modelled.
Void (Geotechnical Stratum type). Representation of the concept of an identified discrete air filled geological feature, including caves and other voids.
Water (Geotechnical Stratum type). Representation of the concept of an identified discrete water filled geological or surface feature including lakes, rivers and seas.
Heat Exchanger. A heat exchanger is a device used to provide heat transfer between non-mixing media such as plate and shell and tube heat exchangers.
Plate (Heat Exchanger type). Plate heat exchanger.
Shell and Tube (Heat Exchanger type). Shell and Tube heat exchanger.
Turnout Heating (Heat Exchanger type). A device used to remove snow from railways. E.g. electric heating device, gas heater
Humidifier. A humidifier is a device that adds moisture into the air.
Adiabatic Air Washer (Humidifier type). Water vapor is added into the airstream through adiabatic evaporation using an air washing element.
Adiabatic Atomizing (Humidifier type). Water vapor is added into the airstream through adiabatic evaporation using an atomizing element.
Adiabatic Compressed Air Nozzle (Humidifier type). Water vapor is added into the airstream through adiabatic evaporation using a compressed air nozzle.
Adiabatic Pan (Humidifier type). Water vapor is added into the airstream through adiabatic evaporation using a pan.
Adiabatic Rigid Media (Humidifier type). Water vapor is added into the airstream through adiabatic evaporation using a rigid media.
Adiabatic Ultrasonic (Humidifier type). Water vapor is added into the airstream through adiabatic evaporation using an ultrasonic element.
Adiabatic Wetted Element (Humidifier type). Water vapor is added into the airstream through adiabatic evaporation using a wetted element.
Assisted Butane (Humidifier type). Water vapor is added into the airstream through water heated evaporation using a butane heater.
Assisted Electric (Humidifier type). Water vapor is added into the airstream through water heated evaporation using an electric heater.
Assisted Natural Gas (Humidifier type). Water vapor is added into the airstream through water heated evaporation using a natural gas heater.
Assisted Propane (Humidifier type). Water vapor is added into the airstream through water heated evaporation using a propane heater.
Assisted Steam (Humidifier type). Water vapor is added into the airstream through water heated evaporation using a steam heater.
Steam Injection (Humidifier type). Water vapor is added into the airstream through direct steam injection.

Impact Protection Device. A impact protection device is a component used to protect other built elements from kinetic damage. impact protection devices currently come in different varieties:
- A vibration damper used to minimize the effects of vibration in a structure by dissipating kinetic energy. The damper may be passive (elastic, frictional, inertia) or active (in a system using sensors and actuators).
- A vibration isolator is a device used to minimize the effects of vibration transmissibility in a structure.
- Impact devices that dissipate kinetic energy from impacting elements (such as vehicles) by deformation or elastic mechanics.

Bumper (Impact Protection Device Type). A bumper is a buffer object at end of track that prevents driving over. It can be fixed on rails or the track panel, or can also be a natural element (e.g. rock, sand).
Crash Cushion (Impact Protection Device Type). Refers to road vehicle energy absorption device installed in front of one or more hazards to reduce the severity of impact.

Damping System (Impact Protection Device Type). An elastic element inserted between the superstructure (track and plate on slab track or ballast bed with ballast inserted in) and the tunnel structure (tunnel floor). Some of the elastic elements have a partial decoupling effect between the superstructure and underground due to vibrations. Both helical springs and elastomer blocks or elastomer strips can be used as suspension systems.
Fender (Impact Protection Device type). A passive or active device formed of a damper and impact panel that is mounted on the quayside to protect against vessel impact.

Interceptor. An interceptor is a device designed and installed in order to separate and retain deleterious, hazardous or undesirable matter while permitting normal sewage or liquids to discharge into a collection system by gravity.
Cyclonic (Interceptor type). Removes larger liquid drops or larger solid particles.
Grease Interceptor (Interceptor type). Chamber, on the line of a drain or discharge pipe, that prevents grease passing into a drainage system.
Oil Interceptor (Interceptor type). One or more chambers arranged to prevent the ingress of oil to a drain or sewer that retains the oil for later removal.

Petrol Interceptor (Interceptor type). Two or more chambers with inlet and outlet pipes arranged to allow petrol/gasoline collected on the surface of water drained into them to evaporate through ventilating pipes.
Junction Box. A junction box is an enclosure within which cables are connected.
Data Junction Box (Junction Box type). Contains cables, outlets, and/or switches for communications use.
Power (Junction Box type). Contains cables, outlets, and/or switches for electrical power.
Kerb. A border of stone, concrete or other rigid material formed at the edge of the carriageway or footway.
Lamp. A lamp is an artificial light source such as a light bulb or tube.
Compact Fluorescent (Lamp type). A fluorescent lamp having a compact form factor produced by shaping the tube.
Fluorescent Lamp (Lamp type). A typically tubular discharge lamp in which most of the light is emitted by one or several layers of phosphors excited by ultraviolet radiation from the discharge.
Halogen (Lamp type). An incandescent lamp in which a tungsten filament is sealed into a compact transport envelope filled with an inert gas and a small amount of halogen such as iodine or bromine.
High Pressure Mercury (Lamp type). A discharge lamp in which most of the light is emitted by exciting mercury at high pressure.
High Pressure Sodium (Lamp type). A discharge lamp in which most of the light is emitted by exciting sodium at high pressure.
LED (Lamp type). A solid state lamp that uses light-emitting diodes as the source of light.
Metal Halide (Lamp type). A discharge lamp in which most of the light is emitted by exciting a metal halide.
OLED Lamp (Lamp type). A solid state lamp that uses light-emitting diodes as the source of light whose emissive electroluminescent layer is composed of a film of organic compounds.
Tungsten Filament Lamp (Lamp type). A lamp that emits light by passing an electrical current through a tungsten wire filament in a near vacuum.
Light Fixture. A light fixture is a container that is designed for the purpose of housing one or more lamps and optionally devices that control, restrict or vary their emission.

Direction Source (Light fixture type). A light fixture that is considered to have a length or surface area from which it emits light in a direction. A light fixture containing one or more fluorescent lamps is an example of a direction source.

Point Source (Light fixture type). A light fixture that is considered to have negligible area and that emit light with approximately equal intensity in all directions.  A light fixture containing a tungsten, halogen or similar bulb is an example of a point source.
Security Lighting (Light Fixture type). A light fixture having specific purpose of directing occupants in an emergency, such as an illuminated exit sign or emergency flood light.

Liquid Terminal. A liquid terminal is a terminating or origination point for the transfer of liquid between distribution system(s). this is the point where the liquid distribution system interacts with the external environment. An example of this is a loading arm for the transfer of liquid from a docked vessel.
Hose Reel (Liquid Terminal type). A Supporting framework on which a hose may be wound whose primary purpose is to connect and interact with the external environment.

Loading Arm (Liquid Terminal type). A loading arm permits the transfer of liquid or liquefied gas from one system to another, through the use of an articulated arm that accounts for the movement of docked vessels.

Mechanical Fastener. A mechanical fasteners connecting building elements or parts mechanically. A single instance of this class may represent one or many of actual mechanical fasteners, for example an array of bolts or a row of nails.
Anchor Bolt (Mechanical Fastener Type). A special bolt which is anchored into concrete, stone, or brickwork.

Bolt (Mechanical Fastener type). A threaded cylindrical rod that engages with a similarly threaded hole in a nut or any other part to form a fastener. The mechanical fastener often also includes one or more washers and one or more nuts.
Chain (Mechanical fastener type). a series of linked metal rings used for fastening or securing something, or for pulling loads.
Coupler (Mechanical Fastener type). A part connecting two rod or bars, such as reinforcement bars.
Dowel (Mechanical Fastener type). A cylindrical rod that is driven into holes of the connected pieces.
Nail (Mechanical Fastener type). A thin pointed piece of metal that is hammered into materials as a fastener.
Nail Plate (Mechanical Fastener Type). A piece of sheet metal with punched points that overlaps the connected pieces and is pressed into their material.

Rail Fastening (Mechanical Fastener type). An assembly of components which secures a rail to the supporting structure and retains it in the required position whilst permitting any necessary vertical, lateral and longitudinal movement. Note: definition from EN 13481-1.
Rail Joint (Mechanical Fastener type). A mechanical assembly with e.g. fishplates to join two rail ends with optional functions (insulation or expansion capacity).
Rivet (Mechanical Fastener type). A fastening part having a head at one end and the other end being hammered flat after being passed through holes in the pieces that are fastened together.
Rope (Mechanical Fastener type). a length of thick strong cord made by twisting together strands of hemp, sisal, nylon, or similar material. used primarily for mooring vessels
Screw (Mechanical Fastener type). A fastener with a tapered threaded shank and a slotted head.
Shear Connector (Mechanical Fastener type). A ring connector that is accepted by ring keyways in the connected pieces
Staple (Mechanical Fastener type). A doubly pointed piece of metal that is hammered into materials as a fastener.

Stud Shear Connector (Mechanical fastener type). Stud shear connectors are cylindrical fastening parts with a head on one side. On the other side they are welded on steel members for the use in composite steel and concrete structures.

Medical Device. A medical device is attached to a medical piping system and operates upon medical gases to perform a specific function. Medical gases include medical air, medical vacuum, oxygen, carbon dioxide, nitrogen, and nitrous oxide.
Air Station (Medical Device type). Device that provides purified medical air, composed of an air compressor and air treatment line.
Feed Air Unit (Medical Device Type). Device that feeds air to an oxygen generator, composed of an air compressor, air treatment line, and an air receiver.
Oxygen Generator (Medical Device type). Device that generates oxygen from air.
Oxygen Plant (Medical Device type). Device that combines a feed air unit, oxygen generator, and backup oxygen cylinders.
Vacuum Station (Medical Device Type). Device that provides suction, composed of a vacuum pump and bacterial filtration line.

Member. An IfcMember is a structural member designed to carry loads between or beyond points of support. It is not required to be load bearing. The orientation of the member (being horizontal, vertical or sloped) is not relevant to its definition (in contrary to IfcBeam and IfcColumn). An IfcMember represents a linear structural element from an architectural or structural modeling point of view and shall be used if it cannot be expressed more specifically as either an IfcBeam or an IfcColumn.
Arch Segment (Member type). Individual segment of an arch structure.
Brace (Member type). A linear element (usually sloped) often used for bracing of a girder or truss.
Chord (Member type). Upper or lower longitudinal member of a truss, used horizontally or sloped.
Collar (Member type). A linear element (usually used horizontally) within a roof structure to connect rafters and posts.
Member (Member type). A linear element within a girder or truss with no further meaning.
Mullion (Member type). A linear element within a curtain wall system to connect two (or more) panels.
Plate (Member type). A linear continuous horizontal element in wall framing, such as a head piece or a sole plate.
Post (Member type). A linear (usually vertical) member used to support something or to mark a point.
Purlin (Member type). A linear element (usually used horizontally) within a roof structure to support rafters.
Rafter (Member type). A linear elements used to support roof slabs or roof covering, usually used with slope.
Stay Cable (Member type). A sloped element suspending a structure (such as bridge deck) from a pylon.
Stiffening Rib (Member type). A linear element added to a flange or a web plate of a girder for local stiffening.
Stringer (Member type). A linear element used to support stair or ramp flights, usually used with slope.

Structural Cable (Member type). A linear cable element used to secure or stabilise a structure by resisting lateral and longitudinal loading  through tension only, but cannot resist compression. usually formed of a flexible cable or wire.
Strut (Member type). A linear element often used within a girder or truss.
Stud (Member type). Vertical element in wall framing.
Suspender (Member type). A vertical element suspending a structure (such as bridge deck) from a suspension cable or an arch.
Suspension Cable (Member type). A suspended element, typically comprising steel wire, sheath, etc.
Tie Bar (Member type). A linear bar element used to secure or stabilise a structure by resisting lateral and longitudinal loading through tension and or compression. usually formed by a solid bar.

Mobile Telecommunications Appliance. A mobile telecommunications appliance is a device that transmits, converts, amplifies or receives signals used in mobile networks.
Note: This entity is used to define specific appliances used in mobile telecommunication networks. General communications appliances and those used in fixed transmission networks should be instantiated using IfcCommunicationsAppliance.
Access Point (Mobile Telecommunications Appliance type). An access point is a device that allows wireless devices to connect to a wired network.
Baseband Unit (Mobile Telecommunications Appliance type). A baseband unit is a component of a distributed base transceiver station for implementing baseband processing functions.

natural_name: Base Transceiver Station (Mobile Telecommunications Appliance type)
description: Base Transceiver Station (Mobile Telecommunications Appliance type). A base transceiver station (BTS) is a network component which serves one cell. It completes the conversion between base station controller and wireless channel, and realizes the wireless transmission and related control functions between base station controller and mobile switching through the air interface.

natural_name: E-UTRAN Node B (Mobile Telecommunications Appliance Type)
description: E-UTRAN Node B (Mobile Telecommunications Appliance Type). An E-utran nodel B is a logical network component which serves one or more E-utran cells. It is the hardware connected to the evolved packet core (EPC), more specifically to the mobility management entity (MME) , which communicates directly with user equipment in wireless way.

natural_name: Gateway GPRS Support Node (Mobile Telecommunications Appliance type)
description: Gateway GPRS Support Node (Mobile Telecommunications Appliance type). The gateway GPRS support node is a component of the GPRS core network that extends the GSM to allow packet switching functionalities. This component is responsible for the internetworking between the GPRS network and external packet switched networks (e.g. the internet).
Master Unit (Mobile Telecommunications Appliance Type). A master unit is a component of a repeater for coupling base station signals.

natural_name: Mobile Switching Center (Mobile Telecommunications Appliance Type)
description: Mobile Switching Center (Mobile Telecommunications Appliance Type). The mobile switching centre (MSC) constitutes the interface between the radio system and the fixed networks. It is an exchange which performs all the switching and signalling functions for mobile station located in a geographical area designated as the MSC area. It consists of a MSC server and a media gateway.

MSC Server (Mobile Telecommunications Appliance Type). The MSC server mainly comprises the call control (CC) and mobility control parts of a mobile switching center (MSC). An MSC server and a media gateway make up the full functionality of an MSC.

natural_name: Packet Control Unit (Mobile Telecommunications Appliance Type)
description: Packet Control Unit (Mobile Telecommunications Appliance Type). A packet control unit performs some of the processing tasks of the base station controller for packet data. It is responsible for data packet, wireless channel management, error sending detection and automatic retransmission.

natural_name: Remote Radio Unit (Mobile Telecommunications Appliance type)
description: Remote Radio Unit (Mobile Telecommunications Appliance type). A remote radio unit is a component of a distributed base transceiver station that converts digital baseband signals into high-frequency (rf) signals and sends high-frequency (rf) signals to the antenna for radiation.
Remote Unit (Mobile Telecommunications Appliance type). A remote unit is a device used to amplify a base station signal.

natural_name: Service GPRS Support Node (Mobile Telecommunications Appliance Type)
description: Service GPRS Support Node (Mobile Telecommunications Appliance Type). The service GPRS support node (SGSN) is a component of the GPRS core network. It is the GPRS support node of mobile station service, and it can achieve mobility management and packet routing and transfer.

Subscriber Server (Mobile Telecommunications Appliance type). It is a database in charge of the management of mobile subscribers. It can be an authentication center (AuC)  or a home location register (HLR).

Mooring Device. A mooring device is an active or passive built element who's primary function is to participate in the mooring of a vessel, this could be in the form of a bollard used as an attachment point for lines or active equipment such as quick release hooks.
Bollard (Mooring Device Type). a short, thick post on the deck of a ship or a quay side, to which ship's rope may be secured. not to be confused with traffic bollards.
Line Tensioner (Mooring Device Type). A mechanical device used to apply a tensioning load to mooring lines to improve vessel stability for port operations.
Magnetic Device (Mooring Device type). Mooring device that uses magnets as the primary method of securing the vessel.
Mooring Hooks (Mooring Device Type). Quick release mooring hooks - an active device used to secure a vessel and provide automated release of vessels.
Vacuum Device (Mooring Device Type). Mooring device that uses vacuum suction as the primary method of securing the vessel.
Motor Connection. A motor connection provides the means for connecting a motor as the driving device to the driven device.
Belt Drive (Motor Connection Type). An indirect connection made through the medium of a shaped, flexible continuous loop.
Coupling (Motor Connection type). An indirect connection made through the medium of the viscosity of a fluid.
Direct Drive (Motor Connection type). A direct, physical connection made between the motor and the driven device.

Navigation Element. A navigation element is an active or passive built element who's primary function is to provide navigational instructions and warnings to vessels, this could be in the form of a floating buoy, a fixed beacon.
Navigation elements can aggregate other components and elements to form the entire structure. this might include a frame structure to form the body, instances of IfcSign for signage or instances of IfcSignal for supplementary lights an/or sound signals.
Beacon (Navigation element type). a fixed vertical structure serving as a navigation mark, to show reefs or other hazards, or provide navigational directions.
Buoy (Navigation Element type). an anchored floating structure serving as a navigation mark, to show reefs or other hazards, or provide navigational directions.

Opening Element. The opening element stands for opening, recess or chase, all reflecting voids. It represents a void within any element that has physical manifestation. Openings can be inserted into walls, slabs, beams, columns, or other elements.

Opening (Opening element type). An opening as subtraction feature that cuts through the element it voids. It thereby creates a hole. An opening in addiion have a particular meaning for either providing a void for doors or windows, or an opening to permit flow of air and passing of light.
Recess (Opening element type). An opening as subtraction feature that does not cut through the element it voids. It creates a niche or similar voiding pattern.
Outlet. An outlet is a device installed at a point to receive one or more inserted plugs for electrical power or communications.
Audio Visual Outlet (Outlet type). An outlet used for an audio or visual device.
Communications Outlet (Outlet type). An outlet used for connecting communications equipment.
Data Outlet (Outlet type). An outlet used for connecting data communications equipment.
Power Outlet (Outlet type). An outlet used for connecting electrical devices requiring power.
Telephone Outlet (Outlet type). An outlet used for connecting telephone communications equipment.

Pavement. Type of built element in a road or other paved area to provide an even surface sustaining loads from vehicles or pedestrians, usually comprising several courses. Also refers to road, runway, or similar construction above the subgrade.
Flexible Pavement (Pavement type). Flexible pavements, including less rigid pavements like rubber.
Rigid Pavement (Pavement type). Pavement substantially constructed of cement concrete.

Pile. A pile is a slender timber, concrete, or steel structural element, driven, jetted, or otherwise embedded on end in the ground for the purpose of supporting a load. A pile is also characterized as deep foundation, where the loads are transferred to deeper subsurface layers.
Bored (Pile type). A bore pile.
Cohesion (Pile type). A cohesion pile.
Driven Pile (Pile type). A rammed, vibrated, or otherwise driven pile.
Friction (Pile type). A friction pile.
Jet Grouting (Pile type). An injected pile-like construction.
Support (Pile type). A support pile.

Pipe Fitting. A pipe fitting is a junction or transition in a piping flow distribution system used to connect pipe segments, resulting in changes in flow characteristics to the fluid such as direction or flow rate.
Bend (Pipe fitting type). A fitting with typically two ports used to change the direction of flow between connected elements.
Connector (Pipe fitting type). Connector fitting, typically used to join two ports together within a flow distribution system (e.g., a coupling used to join two pipe segments).
Entry (Pipe fitting type). Entry fitting, typically unconnected at one port and connected to a flow distribution system at the other (e.g., a breeching inlet).
Exit (Pipe fitting type). Exit fitting, typically unconnected at one port and connected to a flow distribution system at the other (e.g., a hose bibb).

Junction (Pipe fitting type). A fitting with typically more than two ports used to redistribute flow among the ports and/or to change the direction of flow between connected elements (e.g, tee, cross, wye, etc.).
Obstruction (Pipe fitting type). A fitting with typically two ports used to obstruct or restrict flow between the connected elements (e.g., screen, perforated plate, etc.).
Transition (Pipe fitting type). A fitting with typically two ports having different shapes or sizes. Can also be used to change the direction of flow between connected elements.
Pipe Segment. A pipe segment is used to typically join two sections of a piping network.
Culvert (Pipe segment type). A covered channel or large pipe that forms a watercourse below ground level, usually under a road or railway.
Flexible Segment (Pipe segment type). A flexible segment is a continuous non-linear segment of pipe that can be deformed and change the direction of flow.
Gutter (Pipe Segment type). A gutter segment is a continuous open-channel segment of pipe.
Rigid Segment (Pipe segment type). A rigid segment is continuous linear segment of pipe that cannot be deformed.
Spool (Pipe segment type). A type of rigid segment that is typically shorter and used for providing connectivity within a piping network.

Plate. An IfcPlate is a planar and often flat part with constant thickness. A plate may carry loads between or beyond points of support, or provide stiffening. The location of the plate (being horizontal, vertical or sloped) is not relevant to its definition.
Base Plate (Plate type). A plate used to spread load over a surface, such as underneath a bearing or column.
Cover Plate (Plate type). A plate (underneath or above) a flange to provide additional load capacity.
Curtain Panel (Plate type). A planar element within a curtain wall, often consisting of a frame with fixed glazing.
Flange Plate (Plate type). A flange plate in linear members having box or I-profile (e.g. top or bottom flange plate in box-girder).
Gusset Plate (Plate type). a plate or bracket for strengthening an angle in framework (as in a building or bridge).
Sheet (Plate type). A planar, flat and thin element, comes usually as metal sheet, and is often used as an additional part within an assembly.
Splice Plate (Plate type). A plate connecting two members joined at ends.
Stiffener Plate (Plate type). A transversal plate added to a flange or a web plate for local stiffening.
Web Plate (Plate type). A plate connecting flange plates in linear members having box or I-profile.

Projection Element. The projection element is a specialization of the general feature element to represent projections applied to building elements. It represents a solid attached to any element that has physical manifestation.
Blister (Projection Element type). Part of concrete where the anchor for pre-stressing tendon can be embedded.
Deviator (Projection Element Type). Part of concrete where re-direction of an external pre-stressed tendon can be embedded.
Protective Device. A protective device breaks an electrical circuit when a stated electric current that passes through it is exceeded.
Anti Arcing Device (Protective Device Type). An anti-arcing device is an equipment that prevents electric arc.

Circuit Breaker (Protective Device Type). A mechanical switching device capable of making, carrying, and breaking currents under normal circuit conditions and also making, carrying for a specified time and breaking, current under specified abnormal circuit conditions such as those of short circuit.

Earthing Switch (Protective Device Type). A safety device used to open or close a circuit when there is no current. Used to isolate a part of a circuit, a machine, a part of an overhead line or an underground line so that maintenance can be safely conducted.

natural_name: Earth Leakage Circuit Breaker (Protective Device Type)
description: Earth Leakage Circuit Breaker (Protective Device Type). A device that opens, closes, or isolates a circuit and has short circuit protection but no overload protection.  It attempts to break the circuit when there is a leakage of current from phase to earth, by measuring voltage on the earth conductor.
Fuse Disconnector (Protective Device Type). A device that will electrically open the circuit after a period of prolonged, abnormal current flow.

natural_name: Residual Current Circuit Breaker (Protective Device Type)
description: Residual Current Circuit Breaker (Protective Device Type). A device that opens, closes, or isolates a circuit and has short circuit and overload protection.  It attempts to break the circuit when there is a difference in current between any two phases.  May also be referred to as 'Ground Fault Interupter (GFI)' or 'Ground Fault Circuit Interuptor (GFCI)'

Residual Current Switch (Protective Device Type). A device that opens, closes or isolates a circuit and has no short circuit or overload protection.  May also be identified as a 'ground fault switch'.
Spark Gap (Protective Device Type). A spark gap is a device used to connect a circuit to earth in the event of a fault in live circuits.
Varistor (Protective Device Type). A high voltage surge protection device.
Voltage Limiter (Protective Device Type). a voltage limiter is an equipment that prevents the over voltage.
Protective Device Tripping Unit. A protective device tripping unit breaks an electrical circuit at a separate breaking unit when a stated electric current that passes through the unit is exceeded.
Electromagnetic (Protective Device Tripping Unit type). A tripping unit activated by electromagnetic action.
Electronic (Protective Device Tripping Unit type). A tripping unit activated by electronic action.

natural_name: Residual Current (Protective Device Tripping Unit type)
description: Residual Current (Protective Device Tripping Unit type). A tripping unit activated by residual current detection.
Thermal (Protective Device Tripping Unit type). A tripping unit activated by thermal action.

Pump. A pump is a device which imparts mechanical work on fluids or slurries to move them through a channel or pipeline. A typical use of a pump is to circulate chilled water or heating hot water in a building services distribution system.
Circulator (Pump type). A Circulator pump is a generic low-pressure, low-capacity pump. It may have a wet rotor and may be driven by a flexible-coupled motor.

End Suction (Pump type). An End Suction pump, when mounted horizontally, has a single horizontal inlet on the impeller suction side and a vertical discharge. It may have a direct or close-coupled motor.

Split Case (Pump type). A Split Case pump, when mounted horizontally, has an inlet and outlet on each side of the impeller. The impeller can be easily accessed by removing the front of the impeller casing. It may have a direct or close-coupled motor.
Submersible Pump (Pump type). A pump designed to be immersed in a fluid, typically a collection tank.
Sump Pump (Pump type). A pump designed to sit above a collection tank with a suction inlet extending into the tank.

Vertical Inline (Pump type). A Vertical Inline pump has the pump and motor close-coupled on the pump casing. The pump depends on the connected, horizontal piping for support, with the suction and discharge along the piping axis.
Vertical Turbine (Pump type). A Vertical Turbine pump has a motor mounted vertically on the pump casing for either                 wet-pit sump mounting or dry-well mounting.

Rail. A rail is a predominately linear built element that has a special section profile. Rail is distinctive from built elements with similar geometric shapes (e.g. beam, member) that its major function is to ensure guidance of moving for vehicles or other kinds of machineries.

Blade (Rail type). A blade is a machined rail, often of special section, but fixed and/or joined at the heel end to a rail to provide continuity of wheel support. The two switch rails in a set are the two inside rails. A switch rail is described as right or left hand according to whether it is part of a right hand or left hand half-set of switches. Note: definition from EN 13232-1-2004.

Check Rail (Rail type). A check rail is a rail laid close to the gauge face of a running rail which takes part in lateral guidance of the wheel and prevents derailment in small radius curved track and switches and crossings. Note: definition from EN 13481-1.
Guard Rail (Rail type). A guard rail is a rail that limits risk of train derailment, normally not loaded.
Rack Rail (Rail type). A rack rail is a building module for enhancing traction and break performance.

Rail (Rail type). A rail is a special section bar (usually of steel) ensuring the guidance of the wheel of a rolling stock or other heavy machineries. In railway, two rails are combined to form a track.

Stock Rail (Rail type). A stock rail is a fixed machined rail, ensuring the continuity on the main or diverging track with the switch in the open position. The machined part of the stock rail supports its switch rail in the closed position, giving continuity of line through this switch rail. The two stock rails in a set of switches are the two outside rails. A stock rail is described as right or left hand according to whether it is part of a right hand or left hand half-set of switches. Note: definition from EN 13232-1-2004.

Railing. The railing is a frame assembly adjacent to human or vehicle circulation spaces and at some space boundaries where it is used in lieu of walls or to complement walls. Designed as an optional physical support, or to prevent injury or damage, either by falling or collision.

Balustrade (Railing type). Similar to the definitions of a guardrail except the location is at the edge of a floor, rather then a stair or ramp. Examples are balustrates at roof-tops or balconies, or along a bridge or on top of a retaining wall.
Fence (Railing type). Refers to non-load bearing vertical construction, usually lightweight, which bounds or subdivides an external area.

Guard Rail (Railing type). A type of railing designed to guard human or vehicle occupants from falling off a stair, ramp or landing where there is a vertical drop at the edge of such floors/landings, or to provide restraint to an errant road vehicle, installed on the central reserve of or alongside a road.

Handrail (Railing type). A type of railing designed to serve as an optional structural support for loads applied by human occupants (at hand height). Generally located adjacent to ramps and stairs. Generally floor or wall mounted.

Ramp. A ramp is a vertical passageway which provides a human or vehicle circulation link between one floor level and another floor level at a different elevation. It may include a landing as an intermediate floor slab. A ramp normally does not include steps.
Half Turn Ramp (Ramp type). A ramp making a 180° turn, consisting of two straight flights connected by a halfspace landing. The orientation of the turn is determined by the walking line.
Quarter Turn Ramp (Ramp type). A ramp making a 90° turn, consisting of two straight flights connected by a quarterspace landing. The direction of the turn is determined by the walking line.
Spiral Ramp (Ramp type). A ramp constructed around a circular or elliptical well without newels and landings.
Straight Run Ramp (Ramp type). A ramp - which is a sloping floor, walk, or roadway - connecting two levels. The straight ramp consists of one straight flight without turns or winders.
Two Quarter Turn Ramp (Ramp type). A ramp making a 180° turn, consisting of three straight flights connected by two quarterspace landings. The direction of the turn is determined by the walking line.
Two Straight Run Ramp (Ramp type). A straight ramp consisting of two straight flights without turns but with one landing.

Ramp Flight. A ramp comprises a single inclined segment, or several inclined segments that are connected by a horizontal segment, referred to as a landing. A ramp flight is the single inclined segment and part of the ramp construction. In case of single flight ramps, the ramp flight and the ramp are identical.
Spiral (Ramp flight type). A ramp flight with a circular or elliptic walking line.
Straight (Ramp flight type). A ramp flight with a straight walking line.
Reinforced Soil. Soil reinforced or stabilized by some mechanical or chemical method.

Dynamically Compacted (Reinforced Soil type). The method of using dynamic tamping machine usually free falling a heavy hammer from the height, compacting the soil and quickly improving the bearing capacity of the foundation.
Grouted (Reinforced Soil Type). A method of injecting curable slurry into cracks or pores of a geotechnical foundation to improve its physical and mechanical properties.
Replaced (Reinforced Soil type). Dig out the soft soil in a certain range below the foundation ground and then backfill the area with high strength, low compressibility and no corrosive materials.

Roller Compacted (Reinforced Soil type). A kind of compacting method that adopts rolling machinery, repeated rolling and vibration compacts the foundation soil, increasing strength and descreasing compressibility.

Surcharge Preloaded (Reinforced Soil Type). A method that applies load to the foundation to discharge pore water, and the foundation is consolidated to improve the foundation strength. Unloading when the carrying capacity reaches the required level.
Vertically Drained (Reinforced Soil type). A method to set vertical drainage measures in the foundation, so that pore water in the soil is discharged and the foundation strength is improved.

Reinforcing Bar. A reinforcing bar is usually made of steel with manufactured deformations in the surface, and used in concrete and masonry construction to provide additional strength. A single instance of this class may represent one or many of actual rebars, for example a row of rebars.
Anchoring (Reinforcing Bar type). Anchoring reinforcement.
Edge (Reinforcing bar type). Edge reinforcement.
Ligature (Reinforcing bar type). The reinforcing bar is a ligature (link, stirrup).
Main (Reinforcing bar type). The reinforcing bar is a main bar.
Punching (Reinforcing bar type). Punching reinforcement.
Ring (Reinforcing bar type). Ring reinforcement.
Shear (Reinforcing Bar type). The reinforcing bar is a shear bar.
Space Bar (Reinforcing Bar type). A stirrup in pre-stressing system to position TendonConduit.
Stud (Reinforcing bar type). The reinforcing bar is a stud.

Reinforcing Element. A reinforcing element represents bars, wires, strands, meshes, tendons, and other components embedded in concrete in such a manner that the reinforcement and the concrete act together in resisting forces.

Reinforcing Mesh. A reinforcing mesh is a series of longitudinal and transverse wires or bars of various gauges, arranged at right angles to each other and welded at all points of intersection; usually used for concrete slab reinforcement. It is also known as welded wire fabric. In scope are plane meshes as well as bent meshes.
Roof. A roof is the covering of the top part of a building, it protects the building against the effects of weather.
Barrel Roof (Roof type). A roof or ceiling having a semicylindrical form.
Butterfly Roof (Roof type). A roof having two slopes, each descending inward from the eaves.
Dome Roof (Roof type). A hemispherical hip roof.
Flat Roof (Roof type). A roof having no slope, or one with only a slight pitch so as to drain rainwater.
Freeform (Roof type). Free form roof.
Gable Roof (Roof type). A roof sloping downward in two parts from a central ridge, so as to form a gable at each end.
Gambrel Roof (Roof type). A roof sloping downward in two parts from a central ridge, so as to form a gable at each end.
Hipped Gable Roof (Roof type). A roof having a hipped end truncating a gable.
Hip Roof (Roof type). A roof having sloping ends and sides meeting at an inclined projecting angle.
Mansard Roof (Roof type). A roof having on each side a steeper lower part and a shallower upper part.
Pavilion Roof (Roof type). A pyramidal hip roof.
Rainbow Roof (Roof type). A gable roof in the form of a broad Gothic arch, with gently sloping convex surfaces.
Shed Roof (Roof type). A roof having a single slope.

Sanitary Terminal. A sanitary terminal is a fixed appliance or terminal usually supplied with water and used for drinking, cleaning or foul water disposal or that is an item of equipment directly used with such an appliance or terminal.
Bath (Sanitary Terminal type). Sanitary appliance for immersion of the human body or parts of it.
Bidet (Sanitary terminal type). Waste water appliance for washing the excretory organs while sitting astride the bowl.

Cistern (Sanitary terminal type). A water storage unit attached to a sanitary terminal that is fitted with a device, operated automatically or by the user, that discharges water to cleanse a water closet (toilet) pan, urinal or slop hopper.
Sanitary Fountain (Sanitary Terminal Type). A sanitary terminal that provides a low pressure jet of water for a specific purpose.
Shower (Sanitary terminal type). Installation or waste water appliance that emits a spray of water to wash the human body.
Sink (Sanitary Terminal type). Waste water appliance for receiving, retaining or disposing of domestic, culinary, laboratory or industrial process liquids.
Toilet Pan (Sanitary Terminal type). Soil appliance for the disposal of excrement.
Urinal (Sanitary terminal type). Soil appliance that receives urine and directs it to a waste outlet.
Wash Hand Basin (Sanitary Terminal type). Waste water appliance for washing the upper parts of the body.
WC Seat (Sanitary Terminal type). Hinged seat that fits on the top of a water closet (WC) pan.
Sensor. A sensor is a device that measures a physical quantity and converts it into a signal which can be read by an observer or by an instrument.
CO2 Sensor (Sensor type). A device that senses or detects carbon dioxide.
Conductance Sensor (Sensor type). A device that senses or detects electrical conductance.
Contact Sensor (Sensor type). A device that senses or detects contact, such as for detecting if a door is closed.
CO Sensor (Sensor type). A device that senses or detects carbon monoxide.
Earthquake Sensor (Sensor type). A device that senses or detects the seismic wave and measures the seismic intensity in case of earthquake.
Fire Sensor (Sensor type). A device that senses or detects fire
Flow Sensor (Sensor type). A device that senses or detects flow in a fluid.
Foreign Object Detection Sensor (Sensor type). A device that senses or detects foreign objects that shock or break the power network. It may alarm when such accidents happen.
Frost Sensor (Sensor type). A device that senses or detects frost on a window.
Gas Sensor (Sensor type). A device that senses or detects gas concentration (other than CO2)
Heat Sensor (Sensor type). A device that senses or detects heat.
Humidity Sensor (Sensor type). A device that senses or detects humidity.
Identifier Sensor (Sensor type). A device that reads a tag, such as for gaining access to a door or elevator
Ion Concentration Sensor (Sensor type). A device that senses or detects ion concentration, such as for water hardness.
Level Sensor (Sensor type). A device that senses or detects fill level, such as for a tank.
Light Sensor (Sensor type). A device that senses or detects light.
Moisture Sensor (Sensor type). A device that senses or detects moisture.
Movement Sensor (Sensor type). A device that senses or detects movement.
Obstacle Sensor (Sensor type). A device that senses or detects any obstacles. Examples are: detectors sensing objects falling from a bridge, rock-fall detectors, etc.
PH Sensor (Sensor type). A device that senses or detects acidity.
Pressure Sensor (Sensor type). A device that senses or detects pressure.
Radiation Sensor (Sensor type). A device that senses or detects pressure.
Radioactivity Sensor (Sensor type). A device that senses or detects atomic decay.
Rain Sensor (Sensor type). A device that senses or collects rainfall related information.
Smoke Sensor (Sensor type). A device that senses or detects smoke.
Snow Depth Sensor (Sensor type). A device that senses or measures the depth of snowfall.
Sound Sensor (Sensor type). A device that senses or detects sound.
Temperature Sensor (Sensor type). A device that senses or detects temperature.
Train Sensor (Sensor type). A device, usually attached to the rear end of the last vehicle of a train, acting on a fixed equipment to give an indication that the train is complete.
Turnout Closure Sensor (Sensor type). A device that senses or detects the position of a blade of a turnout.
Wheel Sensor (Sensor type). A device that senses or detects the passage of a wheel.
Wind Sensor (Sensor type). A device that senses or detects airflow speed and direction.

Shading Device. Shading devices are purpose built devices to protect from the sunlight, from natural light, or screening them from view. Shading devices can form part of the facade or can be mounted inside the building, they can be fixed or operable.

Awning (Shading Device Type). A rooflike shelter of canvas or other material extending over a doorway, from the top of a window, over a deck, or similar, in order to provide protection, as from the sun.
Jalousie (Shading Device Type). A blind with adjustable horizontal slats for admitting light and air while excluding direct sun and rain.
Shutter (Shading Device Type). A mechanical devices that limits the passage of light. Often used as a a solid or louvered movable cover for a window.

Sign. A sign is a notice on display that gives information or instructions in a written, symbolic or other form. Signs are passive with the most common form of a pictorial panel. An instance of IfcSign refers to the occurrence of an individual panel which can be applied to a surface such as a wall or be aggregated within a Signal Assembly which can include multiple sign occurrences and the associated supporting structural elements (see Signal Assembly for examples).
Marker (Sign type). A Sign type formed of a vertical post (possibly with some lettering or symbols) usually used to delimitate distance or the location of some equipment.
Mirror (Sign type). A sign type that provides information via a reflective mirror surface.
Pictoral Sign (Sign type). A sign type formed of a flat plate with some written or symbolic images on it.

Signal. A signal is an active device that conveys information or instructions to users, by means of an audio, visual signal or a combination of both.
The primary distinction from an IfcSign is that a signal is active and therefore a subtype of IfcFlowTerminal usually requiring power and data connections for its operation.
An instance of IfcSignal represents a singular signalling device in a larger assembled unit or connected system, such as an individual frame within a railway signal, a single light unit in a traffic light system or an audio signal or light mounted on a navigational buoy.
Signals can be physically aggregated together into an assembly which can include multiple signal instances (and also sign instances) and the associated supporting structural elements such as a simple pole or a rigid frame gantry (see Signal Assembly for examples).
Signals can be logically (functionally) grouped together into a signalling system (a type of distribution system) to represent a connected  group of signals for example a group of traffic lights controlling an road intersection.
Audio Signal (Signal type). A signal type formed of an active device conveying information by emitting an audio signal such as a  beep, ring, horn or explosive sound.
Mixed (Signal type). A signal type formed of an active device conveying information in both a visual and audio manner.
Visual Signal (Signal type). A signal type formed of an active device conveying information in a visual manner such as a light, cluster of lights, or mechanical moving shapes.
Slab. A slab is a component of the construction that may enclose a space vertically. The slab may provide the lower support (floor) or upper construction (roof slab) in any space in a building.
Approach Slab (Slab type). Iis part of bridge abutment providing transition from embankment to the bridge
Base Slab (Slab type). The slab is used to represent a floor slab against the ground (and thereby being a part of the foundation). Another name is mat foundation.
Floor (Slab type). The slab is used to represent a floor slab or a bridge deck.
Landing (Slab type). The slab is used to represent a landing within a stair or ramp.
Paving Slab (Slab type). Rigid pavement course of a road or other paved area, usually concrete.
Roof (Slab type). The slab is used to represent a roof slab (either flat or sloped).
Sidewalk (Slab type). The slab is used to represent a sidewalk.

Track Slab (Slab type). A track slab is a reinforced concrete slab or prestressed reinforced concrete slab, which is a main element of slab track. It can be prefabricated or cast on site and may have sleepers embedded.
Wearing (Slab type). The slab is used to represent a wearing surface.
Solar Device. A solar device converts solar radiation into other energy such as electric current or thermal energy.
Solar Collector (Solar Device type). A device that converts solar radiation into thermal energy (heating water, etc.).
Solar Panel (Solar Device type). A device that converts solar radiation into electric current.

Space Heater. Space heaters utilize a combination of radiation and/or natural convection using a heating source such as electricity, steam or hot water to heat a limited space or area. Examples of space heaters include radiators, convectors, baseboard and finned-tube heaters.
Convector (Space Heater type). A heat-distributing unit that operates with gravity-circulated air.
Radiator (Space Heater type). A heat-distributing unit that operates with thermal radiation.

Stack Terminal. A stack terminal is placed at the top of a ventilating stack (such as to prevent ingress by birds or rainwater) or rainwater pipe (to act as a collector or hopper for discharge from guttering).
Bird Cage (Stack Terminal type). Guard cage, typically wire mesh, at the top of the stack preventing access by birds.
Cowl (Stack terminal type). A cowling placed at the top of a stack to eliminate downdraft.
Rainwater Hopper (Stack Terminal type). A box placed at the top of a rainwater downpipe to catch rainwater from guttering.
Stair. A stair is a vertical passageway allowing occupants to walk (step) from one floor level to another floor level at a different elevation. It may include a landing as an intermediate floor slab.
Curved Run Stair (Stair type). A stair extending from one level to another without turns or winders. The stair is consisting of one curved flight.

Double Return Stair (Stair type). A stair having one straight flight to a wide quarterspace landing, and two side flights from that landing into opposite directions. The stair is making a 90° turn. The direction of traffic is determined by the walking line.
Half Turn Stair (Stair type). A stair making a 180° turn, consisting of two straight flights connected
Half Winding Stair (Stair type). A stair consisting of one flight with one half winder, which makes a 180° turn. The orientation of the turn is determined by the walking line.
Ladder (Stair type). a piece of equipment consisting of a series of bars or steps between two upright elements used for climbing up or down something
Quarter Turn Stair (Stair type). A stair making a 90° turn, consisting of two straight flights connected by a quarterspace landing. The direction of the turn is determined by the walking line.
Quarter Winding Stair (Stair type). A stair consisting of one flight with a quarter winder, which is making a 90° turn. The direction of the turn is determined by the walking line.

Spiral Stair (Stair type). A stair constructed with winders around a circular newel often without landings. Depending on outer boundary it can be either a circular, elliptical or rectangular spiral stair. The orientation of the winding stairs is determined by the walking line.
Straight Run Stair (Stair type). A stair extending from one level to another without turns or winders. The stair consists of one straight flight.

Three Quarter Turn Stair (Stair type). A stair making a 270° turn, consisting of four straight flights connected by three quarterspace landings. The direction of the turns is determined by the walking line.

Three Quarter Winding Stair (Stair type). A stair consisting of one flight with three quarter winders, which make a 90° turn. The stair makes a 270° turn. The direction of the turns is determined by the walking line.
Two Curved Run Stair (Stair type). A curved stair consisting of two curved flights without turns but with one landing.

Two Quarter Turn Stair (Stair type). A stair making a 180° turn, consisting of three straight flights connected by two quarterspace landings. The direction of the turns is determined by the walking line.

Two Quarter Winding Stair (Stair type). A stair consisting of one flight with two quarter winders, which make a 90° turn. The stair makes a 180° turn. The direction of the turns is determined by the walking line.
Two Straight Run Stair (Stair type). A straight stair consisting of two straight flights without turns but with one landing.

Stair Flight. A stair flight is an assembly of building components in a single "run" of stair steps (not interrupted by a landing). The stair steps and any stringers are included in the stair flight. A winder is also regarded a part of a stair flight.
Curved (Stair flight type). A stair flight with a curved walking line.
Freeform (Stair flight type). A stair flight with a free form walking line (and outer boundaries).
Spiral (Stair flight type). A stair flight with a circular or elliptic walking line.
Straight (Stair flight type). A stair flight with a straight walking line.
Winder (Stair flight type). A stair flight with a walking line including straight and curved sections.

Surface Feature. A surface feature is a modification at (onto, or into) of the surface of an element. Parts of the surface of the entire surface may be affected. The volume and mass of the element may be increased, remain unchanged, or be decreased by the surface feature, depending on manufacturing technology. However, any increase or decrease of volume is small compared to the total volume of the element.
Defect (Surface feature type). Detected defect on the surface of an element, such as corroded or eroded area.
Hatch Marking (Surface Feature type). surface markings defined by enclosed 2d shape with defined hatch fillings.
Line Marking (Surface feature type). 2D lines painted on pavement surfaces to form boundaries, centrelines and edge markings.
Mark (Surface feature type). A point, line, cross, or other mark, applied for example for easier adjustment of elements during assembly.
Non-skid Surfacing (Surface feature type). Paint or surfacing to prevent sliding or skidding.
Pavement Surface Marking (Surface feature type). Painted or chemical lines or symbols on the surface of pavements (a road or paved area)
Rumble Strip (Surface Feature type). Raised and often textured strips on road center line or on shoulder, or across lanes to alert drivers by vibration and noise. Also Jiggle bars.
Symbol Marking (Surface feature type). Surface markings that convey information in the form of symbols and shapes such as arrows, text or pictorial symbols.

Tag (Surface Feature type). A name tag, which allows to identify an element during production, delivery and assembly.  May be manufactured in different ways, e.g. by printing or punching the tracking code onto the element or by attaching an actual tag.
Transverse Rumble Strip (Surface feature type). Type of rumble strip running across lane(s).

Treatment (Surface Feature type). A subtractive surface feature, e.g. grinding, or an additive surface feature, e.g. coating, or an impregnating treatment, or a series of any of these kinds of treatments.
Switching Device. A switch is used in a cable distribution system (electrical circuit) to control or modulate the flow of electricity.
Contactor (Switching Device type). An electrical device used to control the flow of power in a circuit on or off.
Dimmer Switch (Switching Device type). A dimmer switch has variable positions, and may adjust electrical power or other setting (according to the switched port type).
Emergency Stop (Switching Device type). An emergency stop device acts to remove as quickly as possible any danger that may have arisen unexpectedly.
Keypad (Switching Device type). A set of buttons or switches, each potentially applicable to a different device.
Momentary Switch (Switching Device Type). A momentary switch has no position, and may trigger some action to occur.

Relay (Switching Device type). A device designed to produce sudden predetermined changes in one or more electric output circuits, when certain conditions are fulfilled in the electric input circuits controlling the device. Note: definition from IEC 60050 151-13-31.
Selector Switch (Switching Device Type). A selector switch has multiple positions, and may change the source or level of power or other setting (according to the switched port type).
Starter (Switching Device type). A starter is a switch which in the closed position controls the application of power to an electrical device.

natural_name: Start and Stop Equipment (Switching Device Type)
description: Start and Stop Equipment (Switching Device Type). A switch for alternatively closing and opening one or more electric circuits.
Switch Disconnector (Switching Device Type). A switch disconnector is a switch which in the open position satisfies the isolating requirements specified for a disconnector.
Toggle Switch (Switching Device Type). A toggle switch has two positions, and may enable or isolate electrical power or other setting (according to the switched port type).
System Furniture Element. A system furniture element defines components of modular furniture which are not directly placed in a building structure but aggregated inside furniture.
Panel (System Furniture Element type). Vertical panel used to divide work spaces.
Subrack (System Furniture Element type). A subrack is a part of technical cabinet which is used to store and mount pluggable electric subunits.
Work Surface (System Furniture Element type). Workstation countertop.
Tank. A tank is a vessel or container in which a fluid or gas is stored for later use.
Basin (Tank type). An arbitrary open tank type.

Break Pressure (Tank type). An open container that breaks the hydraulic pressure in a distribution system, typically located between the fluid reservoir and the fluid supply points. A typical break pressure tank allows the flow to discharge into the atmosphere, thereby reducing its hydrostatic pressure to zero.

Expansion Tank (Tank type). A closed container used in a closed fluid distribution system to mitigate the effects of thermal expansion or water hammer. The tank is typically constructed with a diaphragm dividing the tank into two sections, with fluid on one side of the diaphragm and air on the other. One example application is when connected to the primary circuit of a hot water system to accommodate the increase in volume of the water when it is heated.

Feed and Expansion Tank (Tank type). An open tank that is used for both storage and thermal expansion. A typical example is a tank used to store make-up water at ambient pressure for supply to a hot water system, simultaneously accommodating increases in volume of the water when heated.
Oil Retention Tray (Tank type). An open container for environmental protection and storage of chemical products.

Pressure Vessel (Tank type). A closed container used for storing fluids or gases at a pressure different from the ambient pressure. A pressure vessel is typically rated by an authority having jurisdiction for the operational pressure.

Storage Tank (Tank type). An open or closed container used for storing a fluid at ambient pressure and from which it can be supplied to the fluid distribution system. There are many examples of storage tanks, such as potable water storage tanks, fuel storage tanks, etc.
Vessel (Tank type). An arbitrary closed tank type.
Tendon. A tendon is a steel element such as a wire, cable, bar, rod, or strand used to impart prestress to concrete when the element is tensioned.
Bar (Tendon type). The tendon is configured as a bar.
Coated (Tendon type). The tendon is coated.
Strand (Tendon type). The tendon is a strand.
Wire (Tendon type). The tendon is a wire.
Tendon Anchor. A tendon anchor is the end connection for tendons in prestressed or posttensioned concrete.
Coupler (Tendon Anchor type). The anchor is an intermediate device which connects two tendons.
Fixed End (Tendon Anchor type). The anchor fixes the end of a tendon.
Tensioning End (Tendon Anchor type). The anchor is used or can be used to prestress the tendon.
Tendon Conduit. A TendonConduit represents the components of the conduit system for tendons embedded in concrete structure.
Coupler (Tendon Conduit type). A part to connect the conduits located in two different deck segments and related to the same tendon.
Diabolo (Tendon Conduit type). A part of tendon conduit associated to deviator.
Duct (Tendon Conduit type). A Sleeve or duct is related to the thickness of the conduit depending on the conduit, either cast into the concrete structure or placed adjacent to it.
Grouting Duct (Tendon Conduit type). An additional small conduit connected to the main conduit to allow grouting in case of bonded post-tensioning, such as  Grout inlet, Grout outlet and Grout vent.
Trumpet (Tendon Conduit type). A specific part of conduit which has to be widened when reaching the tendon anchor because the strands are connected individually on the anchor.
Track Element. A track element is a built element used specifically in the track domain in railway.
Blocking Device (Track Element type). A device composed of pneumatic, mechanic or electric components causing the braking of a train in case of emergency.
Derailer (Track element type). A fixed device which, when placed on the rail, derails the wheels of a vehicle, and serves to protect a converging line. Note: definition from IEC 60050-821.

Frog (Track Element type). A frog is an arrangement ensuring the intersection of two opposite running edges of turnouts or diamond crossings and having one crossing vee and two wing rails. Note: definition from EN 13232-1-2004.

natural_name: Half Set of Blades (Track Element Type)
description: Half Set of Blades (Track Element Type). A half set of blades consists of one stock rail and its switch rail complete with small fittings. It is right or left hand as seen by an observer in the centre of the track facing the switch heel from the switch toe. Note: definition from EN 13232-1-2004.
Sleeper (Track element type). A sleeper is a track element that supports running rails, guard rails and check rails usually at right angles to its axis.
Speed Regulator (Track Element type). A device composed of pneumatic, mechanic or electric components causing the breaking of a train in case of emergency.

natural_name: Track End of Alignment (Track Element type)
description: Track End of Alignment (Track Element type). A track end of alignment is a special functional installation such as axle-gauge changeover point or transporter wagon loading point.
Vehicle Stop (Track Element type). A fixed installation at the end of the track which stops any vehicle movement (e.g., buffer stop, sand hump, etc.).
Transformer. A transformer is an inductive stationary device that transfers electrical energy from one circuit to another.

Chopper (Transformer type). A chopper is an electronic power DC convertor without an intermediate AC link giving a variable output voltage by varying the periods of conduction and non-conduction in an adjustable ratio.
Combined Transformer (Transformer type). A transformer that changes different quantities between circuits.
Current Transformer (Transformer type). A transformer that changes the current between circuits.
Frequency Transformer (Transformer type). A transformer that changes the frequency between circuits.
Inverter (Transformer type). A transformer that converts from direct current (DC) to alternating current (AC).
Rectifier (Transformer type). A transformer that converts from alternating current (AC) to direct current (DC).
Voltage Transformer (Transformer type). A transformer that changes the voltage between circuits.

Transport Element. A transport element is a generalization of all transport related objects that move people, animals or goods within a Facility. The IfcTransportElement defines the occurrence of a transport element, that (if given), is expressed by the IfcTransportElementType.
Craneway (Transport Element type). A crane way system, normally including the crane rails, fasteners and the crane. It is primarily used to move heavy goods in a factory or other industry buildings.
Elevator (Transport Element type). Elevator or lift being a transport device to move people of good vertically.
Escalator (Transport Element type). Escalator being a transport device to move people. It consists of individual linked steps that move up and down on tracks while keeping the threads horizontal.
Hauling Gear (Transport element type). A device used for hauling goods.
Lifting Gear (Transport Element type). A device used for lifting or lowering heavy goods. It may be manually operated or electrically or pneumatically driven.
Moving Walkway (Transport Element type). Moving walkway being a transport device to move people horizontally or on an incline. It is a slow conveyor belt that transports people.
Tube Bundle. A tube bundle is a device consisting of tubes and bundles of tubes used for heat transfer and contained typically within other energy conversion devices, such as a chiller or coil.
Finned (Tube Bundle type). Finned tube bundle type.
Unitary Control Element. A unitary control element combines a number of control components into a single product, such as a thermostat or humidistat.
Alarm Panel (Unitary Control Element type). A control element at which alarms are annunciated.

natural_name: Base Station Controller (Unitary Control Element type)
description: Base Station Controller (Unitary Control Element type). A base station controller (BSC) is a network component with the functions for controlling one or more base transceiver stations. BSC is responsible for the management of various interfaces, wireless resources and parameters, the signalling processing of call establishment and the channel allocation in the cell.
Combined (Unitary Control Element type). Combination of at least two predefined types of unitary control element.
Control Panel (Unitary Control Element type). A control element at which devices that control or monitor the operation of a site, building or part of a building are located

natural_name: Gas Detection Panel (Unitary Control Element type)
description: Gas Detection Panel (Unitary Control Element type). A control element at which the detection of gas is annunciated.
Humidistat (Unitary Control Element type). A control element that senses and regulates the humidity of a system or space so that the humidity is maintained near a desired setpoint.
Indicator Panel (Unitary Control Element type). A control element at which equipment operational status, condition, safety state or other required parameters are indicated.
Mimic Panel (Unitary Control Element type). A control element at which information that is available elsewhere is repeated or 'mimicked'.
Thermostat (Unitary Control Element type). A control element that senses and regulates the temperature of an element, system or space so that the temperature is maintained near a desired setpoint.
Weather Station (Unitary Control Element type). A control element that senses multiple climate properties such as temperature, humidity, pressure, wind, and rain.
Unitary Equipment. Unitary equipment typically combine a number of components into a single product, such as air handlers, pre-packaged rooftop air-conditioning units, heat pumps, and split systems.
Air Conditioning Unit (Unitary Equipment Type). A unitary packaged air-conditioning unit typically used in residential or light commercial applications.
Air Handler (Unitary Equipment type). A unitary air handling unit typically containing a fan, economizer, and coils.
Dehumidifier (Unitary Equipment type). A unitary packaged dehumidification unit.  Note: units supporting multiple modes (dehumidification, cooling, and/or heating) should use AIRCONDITIONINGUNIT.
Rooftop Unit (Unitary Equipment type). A packaged assembly that is either field-erected or manufactured atop the roof of a large residential or commercial building and acts as a unitary component.
Split System (Unitary Equipment type). A system which separates the compressor from the evaporator, but acts as a unitary component typically within residential or light commercial applications.
Valve. A valve is used in a building services piping distribution system to control or modulate the flow of the fluid.
Air Release (Valve type). Valve used to release air from a pipe or fitting.
Anti Vacuum (Valve type). Valve that opens to admit air if the pressure falls below atmospheric pressure.
Changeover Valve (Valve type). Valve that enables flow to be switched between pipelines (3 or 4 port).
Check Valve (Valve type). Valve that permits water to flow in one direction only and is enclosed when there is no flow (2 port).
Commissioning Valve (Valve type). Valve used to facilitate commissioning of a system (2 port).
Diverting (Valve type). Valve that enables flow to be diverted from one branch of a pipeline to another (3 port).
Double Check (Valve type). An assembly that incorporates two valves used to prevent backflow.
Double Regulating (Valve type). Valve used to facilitate regulation of fluid flow in a system.
Draw Off Cock (Valve type). A valve used to remove fluid from a piping system.
Faucet (Valve type). Faucet valve typically used as a flow discharge.
Flushing (Valve type). Valve that flushes a predetermined quantity of water to cleanse a toilet, urinal, etc.
Gas Cock (Valve type). Valve that is used for controlling the flow of gas.
Gas Tap (Valve type). Gas tap typically used for venting or discharging gas from a system.
Isolating (Valve type). Valve that closes off flow in a pipeline.
Mixing Valve (Valve type). Valve that enables flow from two branches of a pipeline to be mixed together (3 port).
Pressure Reducing (Valve type). Valve that reduces the pressure of a fluid immediately downstream of its position in a pipeline to a preselected value or by a predetermined ratio.
Pressure Relief (Valve type). Spring or weight loaded valve that automatically discharges to a safe place fluid that has built up to excessive pressure in pipes or fittings.
Regulating Valve (Valve type). Valve used to facilitate regulation of fluid flow in a system.
Safety Cut-Off (Valve type). Valve that closes under the action of a safety mechanism such as a drop weight, solenoid etc.
Steam Trap (Valve type). Valve that restricts flow of steam while allowing condensate to pass through.
Stopcock (Valve type). An isolating valve used on a domestic water service.
Vehicle. A Vehicle.
Cargo (Vehicle type). A mobile transport element that represents a discrete unit of cargo managed by a facility.
Rolling Stock (Vehicle type). Refers to railway vehicles, including both powered and unpowered vehicles, for example locomotives, railroad cars, coaches, private railroad cars and wagons.
Vehicle (Vehicle type). a generalisation of a vehicle that interacts with a facility (e.g. as a user/customer) or as a specified operational asset within the facility.
Air Vehicle (Vehicle type). A specialisation of a vehicle that represents powered and unpowered flying vehicles, such as airplanes, helicopters, gliders etc.
Marine Vehicle (Vehicle type). A specialisation of a vehicle that operates on water as a marine vessel.
Tracked Vehicle (Vehicle type). A specialisation of a vehicle that operates on land tracked (Caterpillar) vehicle.
Wheeled Vehicle (Vehicle type). A specialisation of a vehicle that operates on land as a multi wheeled vehicle such as a car, lorry, forklift etc.

Vibration Damper. A vibration damper is a device used to minimize the effects of vibration in a structure by dissipating kinetic energy. The damper may be passive (elastic, frictional, inertia) or active (in a system using sensors and actuators).
Vibration Isolator. A vibration isolator is a device used to minimize the effects of vibration transmissibility in a structure.
Base (Vibration Isolator type). Base isolator preventing transfer of energy from the ground to the structure.
Compression (Vibration Isolator type). Compression type vibration isolator.
Spring (Vibration Isolator type). Spring type vibration isolator.

Voiding Feature. A voiding feature is a modification of an element which reduces its volume. Such a feature may be manufactured in different ways, for example by cutting, drilling, or milling of members made of various materials, or by inlays into the formwork of cast members made of materials such as concrete.
Chamfer (Voiding feature type). A skewed plane end cut, removing material only across a part of the profile of the voided element.

Cutout (Voiding feature type). An internal cutout (creating an opening) or external cutout (creating a recess) of arbitrary shape.  The edges between cutting planes may be overcut or undercut, i.e. rounded.

Edge (Voiding feature type). A shape modification along an edge of the element with the edge length as the predominant dimension of the feature, and feature profile dimensions which are typically much smaller than the edge length.  Can for example be a chamfer edge (differentiated from a chamfer by its ratio of dimensions and thus usually manufactured differently), rounded edge (a convex edge feature), or fillet edge (a concave edge feature).
Hole (Voiding feature type). A circular or slotted or threaded hole, typically but not necessarily of smaller dimension than what would be considered a cutout.
Miter (Voiding feature type). A skewed plane end cut, removing material across the entire profile of the voided element.
Notch (Voiding feature type). An external cutout of with a mostly rectangular cutting profile.  The edges between cutting planes may be overcut or undercut, i.e. rounded.

Wall. The wall represents a vertical construction that may bound or subdivide spaces. Wall are usually vertical, or nearly vertical, planar elements, often designed to bear structural loads. A wall is however not required to be load bearing.
Elemented Wall (Wall type). A stud wall framed with studs and faced with sheetings, sidings, wallboard, or plasterwork.

Movable Wall (Wall type). A movable wall that is either movable, such as folding wall or a sliding wall, or can be easily removed as a removable partitioning or mounting wall. Movable walls do normally not define space boundaries and often belong to the furnishing system.

Parapet (Wall type). A wall-like barrier to protect human or vehicle from falling, or to prevent the spread of fires. Often designed at the edge of balconies, terraces or roofs, or along edges of bridges.

Partitioning Wall (Wall type). A wall designed to partition spaces that often has a light-weight, sandwich-like construction (e.g. using gypsum board). Partitioning walls are normally non load bearing.
Plumbing Wall (Wall type). A pier, or enclosure, or encasement, normally used to enclose plumbing in sanitary rooms. Such walls often do not extent to the ceiling.
Polygonal (Wall type). A polygonal wall, extruded vertically, where the wall thickness varies along the wall path.

Retaining Wall (Wall type). A supporting wall used to protect against soil layers behind. Special types of a retaining wall may be e.g. Gabion wall and Grib wall. Examples of retaining walls are wing wall, headwall, stem wall, pierwall and protecting wall.

Shear Wall (Wall type). A wall designed to withstand shear loads. Examples of shear wall are diaphragms inside a box girder, typically on a pier, to resist lateral forces and transfer them to the support.

Solid Wall (Wall type). A massive wall construction for the wall core being the single layer or having multiple layers attached. Such walls are often masonry or concrete walls (both cast in-situ or precast) that are load bearing and fire protecting.
Standard Wall (Wall type). A standard wall, extruded vertically with a constant thickness along the wall path.
Wave Wall (Wall type). Protective wall or screen to block overtopping and impact of waves across a breakwater

Wall Standard Case. The IfcWallStandardCase defines a wall with certain constraints for the provision of parameters and with certain constraints for the geometric representation. The IfcWallStandardCase handles all cases of walls, that are extruded vertically:

Waste Terminal. A waste terminal has the purpose of collecting or intercepting waste from one or more sanitary terminals or other fluid waste generating equipment and discharging it into a single waste/drainage system.
Floor Trap (Waste Terminal type). Pipe fitting, set into the floor, that retains liquid to prevent the passage of foul air
Floor Waste (Waste Terminal type). Pipe fitting, set into the floor, that collects waste water and discharges it to a separate trap.
Gully Sump (Waste Terminal Type). Pipe fitting or assembly of fittings to receive surface water or waste water, fitted with a grating or sealed cover.
Gully Trap (Waste Terminal type). Pipe fitting or assembly of fittings that receives surface water or waste water
Roof Drain (Waste Terminal type). Pipe fitting, set into the roof, that collects rainwater for discharge into the rainwater system.
Waste Disposal Unit (Waste Terminal type). Electrically operated device that reduces kitchen or other waste into fragments small enough to be flushed into a drainage system.
Waste Trap (Waste Terminal type). Pipe fitting, set adjacent to a sanitary terminal, that retains liquid to prevent the passage of foul air.

Window. The window is a building element that is predominately used to provide natural light and fresh air. It includes vertical opening but also horizontal opening such as skylights or light domes. It includes constructions with swinging, pivoting, sliding, or revolving panels and fixed panels. A window consists of a lining and one or several panels. A window can:
Light Dome (Window type). A special window that lies horizonally in a roof slab opening.
Skylight (Window type). A window within a sloped building element, usually a roof slab.
Window (Window type). A standard window usually within a wall opening, as a window panel in a curtain wall, or as a "free standing" window.
